<TEXT>
beijing the hundreds of chinese who line up daily for visas to 
the united states are being questioned more closely by american 
officials since the government crushed the student democracy 
movement in tianamen square in june 
the americans concern is that those who get visas students in 
particular because they are young and usually single wont come 
back to china once the visas expire 
i challenge anyone to think that 1 percent of those applying 
for visas now wants to come back said embassy spokesman sheridan 
bell 
not only do chinese face closer police scrutiny when applying for 
passports and exit permits from their own government they also must 
convince us visa officers that they will return home 
zhang 23 with blue jeans and a fondness for american slang 
waited in line outside the embassy one recent morning with his 
letter of acceptance from a school in arkansas 
no sweat he said confident of his chances 
he came out two hours later 
no way he said glumly explaining he was turned down because 
he couldnt persuade a us official he would come home 
another student huang a government employee in his 30s was 
accepted into a west virginia colleges computer program 
why wouldnt i come back he said before seeing a consular 
official explaining why he should get a visa i have a beautiful 
baby and a wife and a relatively decent job 
like zhang he was on his second try in a month and like zhang 
he was rejected again 
i heard the record is 15 times huang said 
since junes crackdown the canadian embassy has issued student 
visas more freely than before as a humanitarian gesture it said 
the visa process also has been shortened by weeks 
but a us embassy source who spoke on condition of anonymity 
said it is much harder now for students not sponsored by the chinese 
government to get american visas those whose tuition is 
governmentpaid have the highest return rate because their families 
are forced to pay if they fail to come home they make up most of 
the estimated 40000 chinese now studying in the united states 
spokesman bell said the consular section gave visas to 744 
privately funded students in june when the embassy was closed for 
two weeks and july he refused to say how many were rejected but 
said about 165 such students apply each day 
even allowing for days with low turnouts that would mean five of 
every six applicants have been turned away 
the application process is arduous it now takes about six weeks 
to get a passport and exit permit from the chinese governnment 
compared to about four weeks before the crackdown as police weed 
out those they regard as counterrevolutionaries 
applicants must bring letters from their chinese schools or 
employers certifying they did not take part in the student protests 
but getting a passport said one thin youth was easy compared 
with getting a us visa 
applicants sometimes wait outside for days to get a ticket for an 
interview they line up at 830 am on their appointed day to wait 
for their numbers to be called 
so intense is their desire to get to the united states that many 
applicants spend extra days outside the embassy huddled with other 
applicants endlessly exchanging tips 
i heard that students with full scholarships have a 90 percent 
chance of getting visas those with partial scholarships have a 50 
percent chance and those relying entirely on sponsors to pay have 
almost no chance said a man who was trying for the second time 
a dozen students listened intently 
nursing and teaching majors are no good he said 
authoritatively the united states is short of nurses and teachers 
and theyll think you want to stay it helps if you come from a 
name school or are going to a name school in the united states like 
yale 
the only topic of conversation is how to please the consuls whom 
everyone knows by room number if not name 
no 1 is a woman shes the easiest said the skinny youth 
no 2 we call lefthand because he writes with his left hand hes 
the toughest nos 3 and 4 are about average 
some say friday seems to be the easiest day to get a visa others 
recommend trying for an early morning interview before the consuls 
get tired and hungry a rich sponsor can help but not too rich 
advised one experienced applicant because the consul might think 
youll be tempted to stay 
many chinese expressed bewilderment that the us congress is 
planning to extend the visas of chinese students already in the 
united states fearing theyll be punished for supporting the 
protests but has not relaxed the rules for those who actually 
marched to tianamen square 
our government could close the door at any time said one 
woman whose husband is studying in the united states why does the 
united states say he can stay but not let me go see him 
</TEXT>
