brought to port following their mutiny 150 years ago this week 
across the street is the new haven green where the africans were 
supposedly taken out for daily exercise drawing hundreds of curious 
onlookers 
the aug 26 1839 mutiny and its aftermath galvanized 
abolitionists and led to a us supreme court decision in 1841 
allowing their return to their homeland 
the story of the bid for freedom which began as they were being 
transported from one side of cuba to another is gripping said 
historian howard jones a university of alabama professor who wrote 
a 1987 book on the case mutiny on the amistad 
it is a real epic in that it is the only time in history blacks 
were put in slavery and made it back home jones said in a 
telephone interview 
but the supreme court ruling was no watershed decision because 
the blacks were freed only on the basis of a technicality he said 
the court held only that the spaniards in cuba seeking the return 
of the africans had failed to prove they were their property 
justice joseph story who wrote the courts decision made it very 
clear that if they were legally slaves he could not have freed 
them jones said 
abolitionists saw the decision as taking an important step in 
stamping out slavery jones said in fact it wasnt but the 
impression was it did 
the real importance lies in the opportunity the amistad affair 
gave abolitionists to rally behind the africans to advertise the 
horrors of the slave trade jones said 
abolitionists were determined to get them before the american 
