african leaders declared monday that 
whiterun south africa should end emergency rules and lift bans on 
antiapartheid groups before talks to end racial discrimination 
the leaders seeking a new stategy toward south africa 
conditionally adopted a policy document outlining six preconditions 
for talks between the south african government and opposition groups 
they said the conditions long demanded by african national 
congress guerrillas were needed to create a climate necessary for 
negotiations the congress drafted the summit declaration itself 
the document said talks could create the possibility to end 
apartheid through negotiations it said the government of south 
africa had the urgent responsibility to accept such talks 
the fourday african summit was attended by seven african heads 
of state on its opening day monday 
its declaration adopted by the 16member organization of african 
unity ad hoc committee on southern africa will be presented to the 
next summit of the 101member nonaligned movement in belgrade next 
month 
