the us government and the tuna fishing 
industry warned monday that us trade would be hurt and dolphins 
would gain little if observers were required to monitor 
dolphinkilling by every foreign tuna boat 
a lawyer for environmental groups told a federal judge that us 
law requires foreignowned tuna boats selling to the united states 
to meet the same standard as domestic boats an observer on every 
boat to monitor and prevent needless killing of dolphins during tuna 
fishing 
but lawyers for the government and the domestic industry 
disagreed 
congress recognized that immediate compliance for the foreign 
fleets would be impossible justice department lawyer charles 
brooks told us district judge thelton henderson 
brooks contended the law allowed commerce secretary robert 
mosbacher to determine that only onethird of the foreign boats had 
to carry observers this year federal law forbids the united states 
to buy tuna products from any nation that violates the observer 
standards 
if 100 percent coverage were required foreign fleets would 
simply stop selling their tuna to us companies and trade instead 
with other nations that do not regulate dolphinkilling said david 
burney lawyer for the us tuna foundation an industry group 
such a requirement would precipitously cause these nations to 
abandon their participation in the only program that exists to 
protect the dolphins martin hochman lawyer for the national 
oceanic and atmospheric administration told reporters 
henderson said he would rule in several days on whether the law 
requires every foreign boat to carry an observer 
in january the judge issued an injunction requiring all us 
tuna boats to carry observers rejecting the governments argument 
that a budget shortage justified a reduction in observer coverage 
hochman said congress later approved the money needed for complete 
coverage 
the dolphins which swim above yellowfin tuna are killed when 
caught in nets cast to catch tuna below the surface the observers 
are there to see that boats comply with a law requiring use of the 
best available technology to avoid needless killings 
brooks the governments lawyer agreed with environmental groups 
that foreign boats kill more dolphins but he said not enough money 
and trained observers are available for 100 percent coverage of the 
foreign boats brooks argued that onethird of the boats was a large 
enough sample to tell whether the fleet was complying with us laws 
however joshua flom lawyer for the earth island institute and 
the marine mammal fund said congress had rejected the same argument 
as a justification for less than 100percent observer coverage of 
us tuna boats 
boats behave very differently if they have an observer on 
board flom said why would congress require something more 
extensive for the domestic fleet than for the foreign fleet 
