tropical storm erin rolled over the open atlantic 
monday holding a course that will keep it far from the united 
states according to the national hurricane center 
it looks like it will eventually turn northward and be of 
primary interest to marine interests said hurricane specialist 
hal gerrish the way the environment is shaping up it would be 
extremely unlikely for it to hit the united states 
at 1030 pm edt monday erins poorly defined center was 
located near 255 north latitude and 432 west longitude or about 
1200 miles southwest of the azores island chain gerrish said from 
the center in suburban coral gables 
the storm packed winds of 45 mph sometimes gusting higher in 
squalls as it moved northwest at 11 mph little change in strength 
or motion was expected monday night gerrish said 
tropical depressions become named storms if their sustained winds 
reach 39 mph hurricanes are formed when winds hit 74 mph 
there have been seven depressions in the present atlantic 
hurricane season which runs from june 1 to nov 30 two hurricanes 
have formed so far this year 
