<TEXT>
t franklin williams a geriatrics physician is 
director of the national institute on aging one of the 13 
institutes that comprise the national institutes of health of the 
department of health and human services 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at least 10 million adult americans suffer 
from loss of bladder control including 15 percent to 30 percent of 
older people who live in the community and at least half the 15 
million residents of nursing homes 
contrary to what many people think most incontinence in active 
older people as well as nursing home residents can be cured or 
improved treatments include drugs surgery and behavioral 
therapies such as bladder training 
incredible as it may seem at a time when almost no health 
condition is taboo most older americans afflicted with urinary 
incontinence have never told anyone not even their doctors 
instead they buy adult diapers and absorbent products to manage 
their secret condition assuming it incurable 
incontinence often causes shame and embarrassment about personal 
appearance and odor incontinent people isolate themselves from 
family and friends they restrict their activities outside the home 
and limit social interactions in many cases they become housebound 
prisoners in their own home 
wellmeaning but uninformed relatives may assume wrongly that 
nursing home care is the only option available for a family member 
with incontinence even more regrettable few nursing home residents 
who were incontinent beforehand or who developed the condition after 
admission have any type of diagnostic evaluation not to mention 
treatment or cure 
although researchers know a great deal about incontinence the 
number of people who are not treated successfully remains 
surprisingly high many people still believe it is due to aging 
agerelated changes in the urinary tract make older people likelier 
to develop incontinence but normal aging isnt the cause 
the most common forms of adult urinary incontinence which 
afflicts twice as many women as men are stress urge and overflow 
leakage of urine during exercise coughing sneezing laughing or 
other movements that put pressure on the bladder is stress 
incontinence people who sense a need to void but cannot hold urine 
long enough to reach a toilet have urge incontinence overflow 
incontinence occurs when small amounts of urine leak from a 
constantly filled bladder 
many cases of urinary incontinence are a mixture of more than one 
type older people who can control their urine but cannot reach a 
toilet because of arthritis or another crippling disability have 
functional incontinence 
often incontinence results from a combination of many factors 
including nerve damage restricted mobility illness confusion and 
medications in some cases it is temporary and can be cured by 
changing medications or by treating an acute illness such as a 
urinary tract infection however many cases are chronic lasting 
indefinitely unless properly diagnosed and treated 
the diagnosis of urinary incontinence includes a complete medical 
history careful physical examination and bladder tests patients 
record in a voiding diary each episode of incontinence what 
they were doing at the time and the amount of wetness the doctor 
also evaluates a persons mental health ability to perform 
activities such as bathing and dressing and living arrangements 
and asks about any associated illnesses operations and current 
medications 
most people with incontinence can be helped for example they 
can learn to control bladder and pelvic muscles through behavioral 
therapies like exercises biofeedback and bladder training 
beneficial drugs include bladder relaxants bladder outlet 
stimulants and estrogens surgery can support the bladder increase 
capacity implant a device to control the flow of urine or create a 
sling to support and compress an open urethra some patients may 
require a combination of treatments as a general rule the least 
invasive or least dangerous procedures should be tried first 
even when permanent improvement isnt possible frequent 
reminders to ask for help going to the toilet and an increase in the 
number of trips may reduce incontinence this technique can be 
especially useful in nursing home residents with incontinence other 
helpful changes include restricting liquids before bedtime 
providing easier access to toilet facilities and if necessary using 
absorbent products or a catheter a thin tube inserted to drain 
urine 
the fact that therapies are often effective makes it particularly 
tragic that so many people with incontinence do not seek treatment 
it is not a normal part of aging and people with this burdensome 
condition can be helped 
for a free fact sheet on urinary incontinence send a postcard to 
the nia information centerui po box 8057 gaithersburg 
maryland 208908057 
the following organizations can also provide more information 
please send a businesssized stamped selfaddressed envelope to 
simon foundation for continence box 835 wilmette ill 60091 
18002374666 or help for incontinent people po box 544a 
union sc 29379 18035797900 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

