trucks equipped with navistars new smokeless 
diesel engine will leave cleaner air in their wake instead of the 
characteristic black smoke of their predecessors officials of the 
truckmaker say 
this is a diesel for the 21st century this prototype model 
already meets the toughest 1994 state and federal pollution 
standards for diesel said vice president john horne of 
chicagobased navistar international corp 
the international 94 smokeless diesel also significantly reduces 
emissions of major pollutants company officials said friday 
trucks equipped with the engine probably will not reach the 
market until 1994 due to testing and fuel requirements the company 
said 
diesel engines commonly are favored by commercial operators 
because they give better fuel economy require less maintenance 
last longer and produce fewer pollutants than gasoline engines 
a major drawback is the smoke they emit federal regulators say 
the smokeless diesels development comes at a time when car and 
truck makers around the world are working to meet new state and 
federal emission guidelines 
by 1994 the us environmental protection agency will require 
that all diesel makers reduce particle emissions by 90 percent from 
1985 standards and cut carbon monoxide and nitrogen oxide levels 
navistars new engine will solve the problem by using a new type 
of catalytic converter to reduce the amount of minute particles 
released to the environment navistar officials said 
the development of lowsulfur fuel also will prevent decay of the 
converter said officials of the company the nations leading 
producer of medium and heavyduty trucks 
emissioncontrol requirements will be so stringent by 1994 that 
manufacturers will virtually have to produce a smokeless engine 
said navistar spokesman bill greenhill 
