mai basic four inc reported a quarterly 
loss monday of 462 million including nearly 40 million in 
unusual charges related to its failed takeover bid for prime 
computer inc and a reorganization 
the tustinbased manufacturer of midsize business computers said 
earlier that it expected the loss for the quarter ended june 30 
which contrasted with a profit of 68 million or 45 cents a share 
for the same period last year 
revenues for the period which is the companys fiscal third 
quarter declined 234 percent to 86 million from 1123 million in 
the 1988 quarter 
on aug 4 natick massbased prime accepted a buyout offer of 
12 billion from jh whitney amp co a venture capital firm mai 
basic four tried to buy all or part of prime for nearly nine months 
recently it offered 525 million for primes minicomputer unit 
mai which is controlled by investor bennett lebow attributed 
the quarterly revenue decline primarily to lost business and 
deferred buying decisions related to the tender offer mai put its 
cost from the offer at 25 million and said a reorganization 
announced subsequently would cost 142 million 
mais president and chief executive officer william weksel said 
the takeover attempt coincided with a decline in the midrange 
computer business he predicted a return to profitability by the 
first quarter of its fiscal year 1990 
for the first nine months of its fiscal year the company 
reported a net loss of 383 million compared with net income of 
187 million or 125 per share for the same period last year 
revenue fell from 3029 million to 2984 million for the nine 
months 
